The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Wednesday, June 22, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Asansol, June 21: A 22-year-old youth was beaten up at a bus stand here this morning when he protested against lewd comments directed against his sister by a group of boys.

 Dinesh Pandey had to be hospitalised after the attack near Chitra cinema hall in Hirapur, about 250 km from Calcutta. Police said he received 16 stitches on his head. His sister is a Class IX student of a local English medium school. The police said a hunt was on but none of the eve-teasers had been arrested till late tonight. 

 Calcutta: The chief minister has called a meeting of all 126 municipalities in the state in August. Municipal affairs minister Asok Bhattacharya said at the meeting, Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee would emphasise the need for the civic bodies to realise revenues and be self-reliant. They would also be told to maintain clear and transparent accounts. Discussions will be held on introducing a double entry system and the need to start area-based taxation of property. 

 Behrampore: Arup Mondal, 14, was beaten to death by his brother Bhajan late on Monday at Joykrishnapur, 240 km from Calcutta. Police did not know the reason for the murder but said Bhajan is absconding.




